Nathan,

I have been using QS since 1975.  I have never used &quot;ax&quot; or &quot;exam.&quot;  The 
whole rationale behind QS is to throw out the accumulated debris of 
centuries of using the Roman alphabet for English and making QS as 
phonetic as possible.  Adding two letters to QS to &quot;compete&quot; with a 
letter in the Roman alphabet always seemed unnecessary to me and it 
undercut QS&#39;s premise.  I also never felt its supposed time-saving worth 
the effort.  Also you have to remember which letter represents &quot;exam&quot; 
and which one &quot;ax.&quot;  Why not just write out &quot;ks&quot; or &quot;gz.&quot;

Paige Gabhart


