&gt; One of the sticking points that I have is that oftentimes Read will 
&gt; make the Quikscript spelling dependent on the Orthodox spelling for 
&gt; one reason for another. The rules around ·ax and ·exam follow this; 
&gt; you’re supposed to use ·ax for ·key·see _only_ when Orthodox uses an 
&gt; X. I never liked this rule.
&gt;
&gt; I think I’m getting a similar rationale for the ·utter-or-not rules 
&gt; for -tion and friends (no ·utter) vs. -en and -on (·utter-before-·no). 
&gt; Is the only way to tell whether an ·utter belongs is to look at the 
&gt; spelling in Orthodox, or is there a aural distinction that Read’s 
&gt; conveying that my California-tuned ears are deaf to?
&gt;
&gt; (As an aside, I’d _love_ to be convinced that ·ax and ·exam are 
&gt; actually labor-saving devices. They seem wholly unnecessary, as 
&gt; there’s still that pesky penlift in both.)
&gt;
&gt; 



