          &lt;div id=&quot;ygrp-text&quot;&gt;
            &lt;p&gt;I’m trying to assemble a Quikscript dictionary. To help
              me not screw up, I’m trying to write rules in Python code
              that I can use to check and make sure that I’m not
              misspelling dictionary entries.&lt;br&gt;
              &lt;br&gt;
              One of the sticking points that I have is that oftentimes
              Read will make the Quikscript spelling dependent on the
              Orthodox spelling for one reason for another. The rules
              around ·ax and ·exam follow this; you’re supposed to use
              ·ax for ·key·see _only_ when Orthodox uses an X. I never
              liked this rule.&lt;br&gt;
              &lt;br&gt;
              I think I’m getting a similar rationale for the
              ·utter-or-not rules for -tion and friends (no ·utter) vs.
              -en and -on (·utter-before-·no). Is the only way to tell
              whether an ·utter belongs is to look at the spelling in
              Orthodox, or is there a aural distinction that Read’s
              conveying that my California-tuned ears are deaf to?&lt;br&gt;
              &lt;br&gt;
              (As an aside, I’d _love_ to be convinced that ·ax and
              ·exam are actually labor-saving devices. They seem wholly
              unnecessary, as there’s still that pesky penlift in both.)&lt;/p&gt;
